ğŸ”’ Encrypted Multi-Client Chat App
A secure, real-time chat application built in Python that demonstrates core cybersecurity principles including Symmetric Encryption, TCP Networking, and Concurrency. This project was developed as part of my Cybersecurity Internship at SyntecxHub.

ğŸ¯ Project Overview
The goal of this project was to create a client/server environment where messages are protected against eavesdropping (Man-in-the-Middle attacks) using industry-standard encryption.

ğŸš€ Features
AES-256 Encryption: Messages are encrypted using the Advanced Encryption Standard (AES) in CFB mode before being sent over the network.

TCP Socket Communication: Reliable data transfer using the Transmission Control Protocol.

Multi-Client Support: The server uses Pythonâ€™s threading library to handle multiple simultaneous connections without blocking.

Safe IV Usage: Each message utilizes a unique, cryptographically secure Initialization Vector (IV) to prevent cryptographic pattern analysis.

Audit Logging: All incoming encrypted traffic is logged to a local file (chat_log.txt) for security forensics and monitoring.

ğŸ› ï¸ Tech Stack
Language: Python 3.x

Library: cryptography (for AES implementation)

Networking: socket (TCP/IP)

Concurrency: threading

ğŸ“‚ Project Structure
server.py: The multi-threaded listener that decrypts messages and logs traffic.

client.py: The interactive interface that encrypts user input and sends it to the server.

encryptor_test.py: A standalone script to verify encryption/decryption logic.

chat_log.txt: The automatically generated audit trail.
